@node "FAQSKey" "Since installing the keyboard is missing or repeating single key strokes!"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Since installing the keyboard is missing or repeating single key strokes!"}

You installed the new input.device provided with poseidon! This new device may
cause trouble when being used on Amithlon.@{par}

Use an editor (e.g. the EditPad) and open the file s:startup-sequence. Now scan
for the line@{par}

PsdLoadModule DEVS:input.device QUIET ;Added by Poseidon-Installer@{par}

and remove it. After reboot the problems should be gone.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSWhich" "Which device must I use?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Which device must I use?"}

This question shouldn't came up, when using the installer script.@{par}

The "OpenPCI.device" is for any system except Amithlon. When using Amithlon it's required
to use the "AmithlonUSB.device" to avoid trouble.

@endnode
@node "FAQSUnableToOpen" "Why do I get an 'unable to open device' error message?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Why do I get an 'unable to open device' error message?"}

This can have several sources. The device name on harddisk must be exact named
like it is after installation. You must not rename it, because it's not working
anymore, even if you change the name in Poseidon, too. Unlike in AmigaDos the
upper & lower case are different.

Even in Poseidon the name must be exact the same. The best is to use the file
selector of Trident only to setup the device name, to avoid any problems.@{par}

The last possible problem is that the device is unable to open, because the unit
you selected does not exist. The driver is using the units starting with 0. The
upper limit is defined by the number of controllers within the system. Important
here is "number of controllers" and not number of PCI cards. Normaly an USB PCI
card adds 2 or 3 controllers to the system, but even this can be different. Even
the number of ports isn't a way to calculate the number of controllers. E.g. If unit
3 is not available on your system, then any unit bigger 3 isn't available, too!

@endnode
@node "FAQSReg2" "ArakAttack is working, but I get error requesters while reading a media?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "ArakAttack is working, but I get error requesters while reading a media?"}

You need to inject the Poseidon keyfile into Poseidon by using the "Inject" menu
item within Trident. It's required, because Poseidon has it's own limitation for
unregistered usage!

@endnode
@node "FAQSReg3" "I own a Highway/Subway/Algor with full Poseidon licence, but I get errors while reading media."
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "I own a Highway/Subway/Algor with full Poseidon licence, but I get errors while reading media."}

You need to register Poseidon, because your licence is limited to
Highway/Subway/Algor cards. When used with another driver Poseidon is still
unregistered and you need to register Poseidon.@{par}

Please consult the Poseidon manual for further information on registration and
keyfile handling.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSFreeze" "Why my system is freezing during or after the reset phase?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Why my system is freezing during or after the reset phase?"}

This is a bug within the amithlon core. This problem can be avoided by using the tool
@{"PCICardReset" link "PCICardReset"}@{par}

In 95% of the freezing cases the amithlon bug is causing it. The tool
@{"PCICardReset" link "PCICardReset"} is niot avoiding 100% of these freezes,
because that's impossible. It also can only handle known cards. Currently it's
only handling cards supported by AmithlonTV and of course USB controllers.@{par}

If you want a real fix you should contact Bernd Meyer and ask for it.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSMouse" "The mouse pointer is jumping around! Why?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "The mouse pointer is jumping around! Why?"}

Well, you're using the limited demo version which is slowing down transfers.@{par}

To remove this limitation you need to register ArakAttack.@{par}

@{b}There is a known Amithlon latency problem, which may cause the same effect
when using high speed devices, even if the driver is registered.@{ub}

@endnode
@node "FAQSUSBController" "Which USB Controllers are supported?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Which USB Controllers are supported?"}

Currently @{"UHCI" link "FAQSUHCI"}, @{"OHCI" link "FAQSOHCI"} and
@{"EHCI" link "FAQSEHCI"} compliant controllers are supported.@{par}

Since these controllers are the most used, this allows you to use nearly any
hardware. Even on board and notebook controller should work.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSUSBSpider" "Is it possible to use the Spider-II card with this driver?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is it possible to use the Spider-II card with this driver?"}

Yes, the Spider-II contains two @{"OHCI" link "FAQSOHCI"} controller
and an @{"EHCI" link "FAQSOHCI"} controller.

This driver supports the full hardware class and not a specific vendor/device
combination, so the vendor doesn't matter.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSUHCI" "What is an UHCI Controller?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is an UHCI Controller?"}

An UHCI controller is beside the @{"OHCI" link "FAQSOHCI"} controller
controlling USB 1.x devices.@{par}

UHCI stands for "Universal Host Controller Interface".@{par}

The UHCI standard is consuming much CPU power and it is the worst of the three
standard controller types.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSOHCI" "What is an OHCI Controller?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is an OHCI Controller?"}

An OHCI controller is beside the @{"UHCI" link "FAQSUHCI"} controller controlling USB 1.x devices.@{par}

UHCI stands for "Open Host Controller Interface".@{par}

The UHCI standard is consuming less CPU power than the UHCI, because there is more stuff done in hardware.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSEHCI" "What is an EHCI Controller?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is an EHCI Controller?"}

An EHCI controller is what is known as USB 2.0 controller.@{par}

EHCI stands for "Enhanced Host Controller Interface".@{par}

Unlike mentioned on other places, EHCI is not full backward compatible.@{par}

The reason why all USB 1.x device are working is that under normal circumstances
the EHCI controller is combined with at least so called "companion" controller
(@{"UHCI" link "FAQSUHCI"}, @{"OHCI" link "FAQSOHCI"}) which is parallel
connected to the same USB port. If EHCI is detecting a low speed device it
simply switches the port to the companion controller which thinks there is a new
device pluged in.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSSPEED" "What different USB speeds exists?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What different USB speeds exists?"}

That's a good question. While developing this driver set I found several
wrong names for a device speed, used by the vendor to suggest faster hardware.@{par}

The following speeds are official:@{par}

Name          USB Type  Mega-Bit/s - Mega-Byte/s@{par}
------------------------------------------------@{par}
Low-Speed  -  USB1.x    1.5 Mb/s   - 196.608 KB/s@{par}
Full-Speed -  USB1.x    12  Mb/s   - 1.57286 MB/s@{par}
High-Speed -  USB2.0    480 Mb/s   - 62.9145 MB/s@{par}

These are the real USB speeds. Effective the real speed is much lower. The
reason is the overhead during transmission and the slow hardware. For example an
USB2.0 memory stick is only able to read around 7MB/s.@{par}

Some vendors are using wrong names. So you may find "Med-Speed" or
"Medium-Speed" on the package. In the most cases this indicates "low-speed".
Also tricky combinations of the word compatibly are used to make devices look
faster. So "USB2.0 compatible - Full-speed" is just a normal USB1.x device.@{par}

Important is that there is "USB2.0" without "compatible". In the other case you
can return the stuff to your locale shop, because of the wrong description on
the box.@{par}

It's always a good idea to look for the official USB2.0 Logo. It's a small plug
looking logo with USB printed on. On the wire you can read the very small word
"certified". A speach bubble is comming from it and says "Hi-Speed".@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSSPEED2" "Is it true that USB2.0 devices are faster when used with an USB1.1 Controller?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is it true that USB2.0 devices are faster when used with an USB1.1 Controller?"}

Yes, that's true! Of course they aren't faster than USB2.x speed, but they may
faster than a compared USB1.x device. Even if some people may say that's wrong.
You just cannot make this conclusion for all USB devices.@{par}

The only USB2.x devices that may run faster than an USB1.x device on an USB1.x
controller are flash memory based devices like card reader and memory sticks.
The USB1.x devices often contain cheap flash memory which isn't able to support
full USB1.x speed.@{par}

USB2.0 devices are required to handle much faster transfer rates, so when used
in USB1.x mode, these buildin flash chips are much faster than the USB1.x data
rate and won't slow down the transfer.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSSPEED3" "Is it true that USB1.x devices work faster on USB2.0 HUBs?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "Is it true that USB1.x devices work faster on USB2.0 HUBs?"}

Yes and no! The transmission to the HUB is much faster, but the HUB itself needs
to communicate with USB1.x speed to the device.@{par}

The CPU load needed when using the HUB is much lower. If you plug in the USB1.x
device into the @{"EHCI" link "FAQSEHCI"} controller (USB2.0) the
@{"UHCI" link "FAQSUHCI"} or @{"OHCI" link "FAQSOHCI"} companion controller is taking over and
the transfer is less effective.@{par}

I don't know if this advantage can be detected, because of the very fast
computer systems we're using.@{par}


@endnode
@node "FAQSUSBDeviceWork" "How did I know which hardware is working and which not?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "How did I know which hardware is working and which not?"}

Well! As always the Amiga driver problem is back for USB, too.@{par}

Thankfully, the USB developers created some standard interfaces like for
massstorage devices. Thanks to the standard interface any massstorage device
will work regardless if it's a harddisk or a memory stick. Same for keyboards
and mice. USB to parallel and USB to serial converter are working, too. There is
no need for specific HUB drivers.@{par}

Paradise? No! On the bad side the USB developers did not do the full job.@{par}

No printer class: Printers may work, if a normal parallel/serial driver is
available printing via usbparallel.device is working. If the drinter vendor is
using a special USB command set the printer will not work at all.@{par}

No scanner class: Scanners need external hardware specific drivers. FxScan is a
good choice here. Take a look on http://www.iospirit.de for further information.@{par}

Thanks to Chris Hodges HID devices like keyboards, mice and game controllers are
freely adjustable. If Poseidon is not able to assign buttons correctly the user
is able to fix this on his own and to set up a personal configuration.@{par}

If you want to be sure the hardware is supported you should borrow it. Especialy
when planning expensive devices this is always a good idea.@{par}

@endnode
