@endnode
@node "FAQSWrite1" "How long did it take to write the driver?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "How long did it take to write the driver?"}

"The driver" isn't completely true. ArakAttack contains 3 different drivers
which are able to work alone. I am also able to create once separate device for
each controller.@{par}

The biggest advantage of using one single device is, that it's saving resources.
Programm code and memory are shared between the different drivers.@{par}

I can't answer the question how long it took to write the stuff. I started in
september 2003, but I didn't work every day and not continuesly on it. Some
times I didn't do anything for around two weeks and then I spend 1 hour here or
I worked 12 hourse until the early morning without having a break. Inbetween
other things were needed. The manual you're reading, the installer and the
automatic archive creation stuff which makes releasing the stuff very easy.
Today it's February, 25 2004 and the programming isn't finsihed yet.@{par}

The whole work wasn't programming at all. USB is very complicated and you need
to understand the basics before you even get something to work. Together all PDF
files are 4.3MB big. The general usb description alone take around 2MB and there
isn't any controller specific word init. I don't take sources and modify then
until they work. I want to understand how it's working, to make a better
product. My driver is completly new and based on the offical specifications.@{par}

Before creating a poseidon device I created a sandbox named envirement which
allowed me to send commands down the usb bus und see how it reacts. Later on I
send little streams. So I looked step by step behind the things. Test envirement
in one hand and the experimental code in the other.@{par}

The source code takes over 1.1MB, but the characters typed during development
are 15 to 20 time higher. Some routines were reprogrammed up to 10 times,
because with the programming of another usb controller hardware other ideas of
optimising came up and I started reworking the code I finished a week ago. The
transfer element creation and checking routines were changed over and over to be
more effective and more cpu friendly. Even now, I have an idea of optimising the
stuff once more.@{par}

That is the reason why my driver is that fast. I spend much time in reworking
the stuff and dropping other mechanisms and tricks. My driver was written for
AmigaOS to ensure maximum performance and not only converted and adapted like
many other stuff.@{par}


@endnode

@node "MAST" "ArakAttack - Main Preferences"

@{MS "Main Preferences"}

These preferences allow to set up a customised driver setup.@{par}

Here is a list of the available gadgets within the window:@{par}

@{code}
@{MS "UHCI Setup"}
@{MS "OHCI Setup"}
@{jcenter}@{"No Power Switching" link "MASTOHCN"}
@{MS "Miscellaneous Setup"}
@{jcenter}@{"Legacy" link "MASTLGCY"}

@{"Save" link "MASTSAVE"}
@{"Reset to Defaults" link "MASTDeFa"}
@{"Abort" link "MASTCANC"}

@endnode
@node "MASTOHCN" "Main preferences - No Power Switching"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "No Power Switching"}

Some AMD OHCI controller have problems with the power management, so this switch is
turing the shit off to work around the bug.

@endnode
@node "MASTLGCY" "Main preferences - Legacy"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Legacy"}

Most USB controllers available on main board support the so named "legacy" mode,
which can be enabled via BIOS. Often this mode is also named "Lowlevel USB" or
"USB for DOS".@{par}

The legacy support allows to use keyboard and mouse with an OS which does not support USB at all.@{par}

To work correctly it's required to disable the legacy support enabled by the BIOS.@{par}

If this is causing trouble, then it's possible to deactivate the legacy handling
within the driver. It's also required to disable the legacy support within the
BIOS to give the driver full control over the USB hardware.@{par}

USB PCI cards don't support legacy, so no problem there.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTSave" "Main preferences - Save"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Save"}

The settings will be saved to disk and the window will be closed.@{par}

@{b}Important! The new setup only get's active if the driver is restarted from scatch.@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTDefa" "Main preferences - Reset to Defaults"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Reset to Defaults"}

This button resets the entire setup to the "factory defaults"!

@endnode
@node "MASTCanc" "Main preferences - Abort"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Abort"}

The window will be closed and the setup will be discarded.

@endnode

@node "AddOn" "ArakAttack - AddOn"

@{MS "AddOn"}

Here are some included tools to make the USB usage much easier:@{par}

@{jcenter}@{"HIDClassPatch" link "HIDClassPatch"}@{par}

@{"PCICardReset" link "PCICardReset"}@{par}

@endnode
@node "HIDClassPatch" "AddOn - HIDClassPatch"

@{MS "HIDClassPatch"}

Poseidon provides it's own input.device replacement, which enables special
mouse/keyboard features. On some Amithlon systems the device is causing massive
keyboard trouble (aka running char). That's what the HIDClassPatch was made for
in the first place.@{par}

If you are using an USB Keyboard without the new input device you may noticed
that the key repeat isn't working. In addition to that several other small
problems and side effects may happen during usage and confuse the user.@{par}

This is no bug within Poseidon. The AmigaOS has no API for inserting key streams
at the source of the stream. There is an other offical solution which is causing
the problems mentioned above, because this API was designed to add simple
hotkeys and not real and complex keyboard interfaces.@{par}

This patch allows - by using an "illegal" ROM jump - to fix any of the problems
by inserting the key codes at the same position the normal keyboard values are
added. Attention! This garantees 100% compatibly with all AmigaOs compatible
programms. This patch is only working with Kickstart 3.1 and may not work with
all versions of it. Of course on Amithlon we have the same ROM, so there is no
problem with it.@{par}

The patch should not crash with the wrong ROM, but if no key repeat is available
the patch isn't installed.@{par}

To install the command just add the "run >NIL: HIDClassPatch >NIL:" line to your
user-startup.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PCICardReset" "AddOn - PCICardReset"

@{MS "PCICardReset"}

@{b}Due the fact I was blamed for telling bullshit on the AmithlonOpen/Amithlon
mailing list, I promised that I would not release this tiny bug fix for free, so
it's only working in combination with a registered ArakAttack driver.@{par}

Feel free to ask Bernd Meyer for fixing the problem! You're also welcome to
thank the lemmings on the mailing list as well.@{par}

It's not my fault, so why should I again fix problems not caused by my
software.@{par}

Welcome on the other side of the fence!@{par}

I am sorry to do that on your (the user) shoulders.@{par}@{ub}


Due a bug in Amithlon the PCI cards stay active during and after reset. This
may freeze the entire system during reboot or when starting the corresponding
driver again.@{par}

It's also possible that the system is freezing just the moment you push the
reset combination on the keyboard. When using USB this isn't happening, but
other cards may react like that. This tool is avoiding the freeze by stopping
the cards. Of course there is no chance to work around the "freeze on system
reset"-bug, but all other problem can be avoided.@{par}

This tool should be started in the user-startup by using "PCICardReset >nil:".
The only important thing is that it must be started before Poseidon is going to
start up.@{par}

Currently PCICardReset is stopping USB controllers and bt8x8 tv cards.@{par}

@endnode

